                        <p>Many of the people who currently work in the pediatrics department never had the opportunity to meet the distinguished pediatrician. </p>
<p>“I wish that I had known Dr. Kiser as he was obviously a remarkable man who was very talented and very generous,” Associate Chair of the Department of Pediatrics Dr. Thomas Kinney, Trinity ’66 and Med ’70, wrote in an e-mail. “He truly had a deep affection for Duke and Duke Pediatrics.”</p>
<p>According to a Duke release, the Kisers gained their wealth by early investment in Food Lion, Inc., when it was still a local grocery store. It was through the company’s success that the Kisers were able to fund their philanthropic activities. </p>
<p>“He was a wonderful community member, but he was very unassuming. He lived very modestly,” Glenn said. “You would have met him and never would have realized that he was a multimillionaire. He was a true philanthropist.”</p>

